Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back. The two umpires and players have made their way out to the middle. Devon Conway and Tom Latham are two openers for New Zealand. Chris Woakes will start with the new ball for England. Let's play...
... THE SECOND INNINGS ...

A solid response with the bat will now be crucial for New Zealand to back up this impressive bowling performance. Even as the ball softened and aged, there was still noticeable sideways movement, and facing the hard new ball will pose a real challenge for the Kiwi batters. England will back themselves to strike early and put the hosts under pressure, setting the tone for what promises to be an intriguing passage of play. Back in a bit for New Zealand's reply.

Well, a quick finish after the Tea break from New Zealand! Having opted to bowl first, Tom Latham and Co. will be pleased to have restricted England to 280. As for England, they will be disappointed, given the position they were in during the second session. At 217/4, they seemed poised for a bigger total but crumbled, losing 6 wickets for just 63 runs. Apart from the 174-run stand between Harry Brook and Ollie Pope - where Brook brought up his century and Pope his fifty - there wasn't much else to cheer for the tourists.

OUT! IN THE AIR AND GONE! Nathan Smith has got the final wicket of the innings. He bowls it on a short of length, around middle, Brydon Carse goes for a hook shot but it gets skied off the top edge. William O'Rourke runs to his left and settles under it at deep fine leg. He has to put the dive in the end out in front to take it with both hands. Smith ends with 4 wickets. England have been bowled out for 280.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Tom Blundell has been proven right. Pitched in short, outside off. Takes off after pitching as Chris Woakes tries to cash on the width given and tries to smack it over deep point but misses. Tom Blundell goes up in appeal as soon as he collects it. No one hears that nick except the keeper. Blundell convinces the captain to take the review. Tom Latham sends it upstairs. UltraEdge confirms a spike when the ball is right next to the bat and the New Zealand huddle is overjoyed.

Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the third and final session of the day. The two umpires and players make their way out to the middle. Gus Atkinson joins Chris Woakes out in the middle. Nathan Smith will finish his over. Let's play...
... DAY 1, SESSION 3 ...

The pair stitched a formidable 174-run partnership for the third wicket, with Brook notching up his second century of the series. Pope fell for 66, and as the saying goes, 'one brings two', William O'Rourke made it true for New Zealand by dismissing Ben Stokes soon after. The loss of two quick wickets left England in a precarious position, and the dismissal of Brook just before the session's end firmly tilted the momentum in New Zealand's favour. With the deck still offering sideways movement, the hosts will be eager to wrap the innings up quickly. Meanwhile, England will aim to push closer to that 300-run mark, which could prove to be a competitive total on this surface. Back in a bit for the third session.

The wicket of Harry Brook right at the stroke of the Tea break has tilted the second session in New Zealand's favour. It was the second session in a row where both teams fiercely vied for control. The tourists held firm for nearly the first hour, with Ollie Pope's dismissal coming right at the hour mark. However, New Zealand clawed their way back with disciplined bowling and crucial breakthroughs, including the dismissal of Brook, have shifted the advantage their way. Harry Brook picked up where he left off after the Lunch break, showcasing his free-flowing strokeplay, while Ollie Pope grew in confidence and accelerated as the session progressed.

OUT! RUN OUT! It had to take something special to get Brook out today! Nathan Smith, from over the wicket, bowls a good length ball, around middle, nips in, Harry Brook nudges it beside the pitch on the leg side and runs a couple of steps further but Chris Woakes is adamant in his crease and sends back Brook.  Nathan Smith is quick enough to get the ball to his right on his follow-through and knocks the stumps down at the batting end with Brook well short of his crease. Brook walks off to a standing ovation. With that, it will be TEA on Day 1!

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks break! The runs have continued to flow for England, with Harry Brook showcasing his class with some sublime strokeplay. His attacking approach has kept the scoreboard moving briskly, putting New Zealand on the back foot. However, the dismissal of Ollie Pope has provided the hosts with an opening, and they will now look to capitalize by targeting the new batter at the crease. England, meanwhile, will aim to consolidate and maintain their momentum. An intriguing passage of play awaits. Ben Stokes is the new batter.

OUT! TAKEN! William O'Rourke has been troubling Pope since morning and he finally gets his man! O'Rourke bangs it into the deck, outside off, Ollie Pope tries to get on top of the bounce and looks to drag the pull from outside off. The extra bounce results in Pope getting a top edge that goes straight up around the short mid-wicket region. Rachin Ravindra at short leg runs to his left and there is a bit of miscommunication between him and the mid on fielder, Matt Henry but eventually Rachin takes it with his hands out in front. The 174-run stand is broken. Pope goes for 66 (78). England are now 217/5.

... DAY 1, SESSION 2 ...

Harry Brook then led England's fightback with Ollie Pope for company through a determined partnership that currently stands unbeaten at 81 off 80 balls. Despite initial struggles with timing, both batters showed grit and aggression to wrestle back some momentum. Brook continued his rich vein of form, racing to a quickfire half-century off just 47 balls, showcasing his intent to dominate the bowlers. Even after the first hour, the ball seamed around enough but it should ease out as the day progresses. Join us at 12.40 am GMT for what promises to be an exciting continuation of this fascinating Test match.

End of an entertaining session! Not much of a surprise when England are batting in Test cricket these days. It was a tale of two halves, with New Zealand dominating the first hour, but an English fightback followed. Winning the toss and electing to field, the hosts made early inroads, with Matt Henry and Nathan Smith each taking two wickets, leaving England reeling at 43/4. Henry, in particular, was consistent with his lines and length and kept the English batters under pressure.

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks break! New Zealand could not have asked for a better start, dismantling England's top four in the first hour. Matt Henry and Nathan Smith have been outstanding with their precision and movement, claiming two wickets each. It will be intriguing to see how the English batters approach the next phase. Will they continue to play their shots and take risks, or will they focus on consolidating and ensuring they bat through this challenging period?

Commentary.Commentary: All in readiness for the action to commence. The early morning overcast conditions have given way to glorious sunshine over the Cello Basin Reserve as the two umpires and players make their way out to the centre. Craig McMillan informs that the first four days of the Test have been sold out. It will be the left-hand right-hand combination of Ben Duckett and Zak Crawley to open the innings for England. It will be Tim Southee to kickstart proceedings with the new ball for New Zealand. Three slips and a gully await. Away we go...

We are moments away from the first ball, but before that, Tom Latham and Ben Stokes will lead their respective sides out for the national anthems. It will be the national anthem of England first, followed by New Zealand's national anthem.

PITCH REPORT - Katey Martin is near the deck. She starts by mentioning that the sun is shining brightly, with a gentle southerly breeze blowing across the ground. This breeze should help keep conditions cooler throughout the day. She observes that the surface isn’t as bright green as it was last year, but the ball is still expected to carry nicely. She notes that there’s something in it for everyone - seamers early on and opportunities for batters later. Katey feels that if the English batters can navigate the tricky early phase, they will have a chance to cash in later in the day.

Ben Stokes, the captain of England, says that they were looking to bat first. Adds that he is pretty happy with the last game where team efforts came but some individual performances like those of Harry Brook and Brydon Carse were good to see. Mentions that it is amazing to be part of this dressing room and he was disappointed with the 1-run loss here in Wellington on the last tour.

The captain of New Zealand, Tom Latham says that they will bowl first. Mentions that it is a traditional Wellington surface and they want to make the most use of it early on. Adds that it is going to be an important first two hours of the Test. Further adds that there is a good crowd that has come in to support the Kiwis. Concludes that whether they win or lose, they are always looking to improve. Feels that this wicket won't turn much.
England (Unchanged Playing XI) - Zak Crawley, Ben Duckett, Jacob Bethell, Joe Root, Harry Brook, Ollie Pope (WK), Ben Stokes (C), Chris Woakes, Gus Atkinson, Brydon Carse, Shoaib Bashir.

New Zealand (Unchanged Playing XI) - Tom Latham (C), Devon Conway, Kane Williamson, Rachin Ravindra, Daryl Mitchell, Tom Blundell (WK), Glenn Phillips, Nathan Smith, Tim Southee, Matt Henry, William O'Rourke.
TOSS - New Zealand have won the flip of the coin and they will BOWL first.

The loss in Christchurch not only stunned New Zealand but also dealt a fatal blow to their World Test Championship final hopes. To make matters worse, the hosts were docked three WTC points for slow over-rate. England faced the same penalty, and both teams will now be cautious about maintaining the over rate in this Test. Both teams have announced unchanged playing XIs a day ahead of the match. Can England sustain this dominant form and make it 2-0? Or will New Zealand mount a spirited fightback? Join us for the ride to find out. Stick around for the toss.

As for England, everything seems to be falling into place for them. Their high-octane approach, rooted in Bazball, has taken the cricketing world by storm, with players like Ben Duckett and Harry Brook leading the charge with explosive performances. Brook’s match-winning century, alongside significant contributions from Ben Stokes and Ollie Pope, proved that the team’s new aggressive mentality is working wonders. England’s bowling, led by the exceptional Brydon Carse, was equally impressive, with Chris Woakes and Gus Atkinson providing the support when needed. With momentum on their side, England are eyeing a Test series win in New Zealand for the first time since 2008.

Starting with New Zealand, they came into this series riding high after an incredible 3-0 triumph over India on Indian soil but were left heartbroken by the defeat in Christchurch. Kane Williamson, returning from injury, showed glimpses of his class but the rest failed to provide the necessary consistency to challenge the English total, and the drop of Harry Brook five times in the field proved costly. New Zealand will need their stars across both departments to deliver to bring the series on level terms. The bowling unit, led by Tim Southee, remains a potent force, and adapting to the challenge of this dynamic England team will be crucial.

Hello and welcome to the Cello Basin Reserve in Wellington for the second Test between New Zealand and England. It promises to be another thrilling chapter in this exciting three-match series. With the tourists leading 1-0, they will be eager to wrap up the series here in Wellington, while New Zealand, who were not at their best in Christchurch, will be determined to bounce back. The weather in Wellington for the second Test looks promising, with sunny spells expected on most days, although the possibility of light showers could keep the pacers interested.
... MATCH DAY ...

We are back. The two umpires and players have made their way out to the middle. Zak Crawley and Ben Duckett will open the innings for England. Tim Southee has the new ball and he is raring to go. Three slips and a gully in place. Off we go...
... THIRD INNINGS ...

Right then, England hold a substantial lead, and we can expect them to bat with the same aggressive approach that characterized their first innings as they look to extend their advantage. This intent could present opportunities for the Kiwi bowlers, who must remain disciplined to prevent the visitors from running away with the game. The movement and bounce off the wicket have been consistent, and New Zealand’s pacers will need to exploit these conditions effectively to keep their team in the contest. Back in a bit for England's second innings.

A hat-trick from Gus Atkinson to wrap up New Zealand's innings! England could not have asked for a better start to the day as they managed to claim 5 wickets in just under 45 minutes to take a hefty 155-run lead. The Kiwis could only add 39 runs to their overnight score of 86 as the tourists just kept chipping away at the wickets. Brydon Carse set the tone with a double strike in the 4th over of the day to remove the two overnight batters and then Atkinson with a hat-trick completed the clean-up job.

OUT! LBW! GUS ATKINSON HAS A TEST HAT-TRICK! This one is bowled fuller and on the off stump, slightly nips in. Tim Southee is caught inside his crease as he tries to play at it with just his hands, gets beaten on the inside edge and the ball thuds onto the front pad. Atkinson does not even bother appealing and is off on a celebratory run. The English fielders go up and the umpire raises the dreaded finger. Tim Southee sends it upstairs, more in hope than anything else. The UltraEdge shows a flat line. The Ball Tracking comes up with three reds with the ball crashing into the middle and the leg stump. New Zealand have been bundled out for 125 runs, giving England a mammoth lead of 155 runs.

Commentary.Commentary: We are all set for the action to start on Day 2. Ben Stokes leads his troops out to the centre. Gus Atkinson will kickstart proceedings with the ball for England. Tom Blundell will face the first ball. Three slips and a leg gully in place. Let's play...

PITCH REPORT - Craig McMillan and Shane Bond are near the deck. McMillan feels that when the sun is out, it is generally a batting day but the warm conditions should also help the bowlers. Bond reckons that there is something in the deck for everyone. Adds that it may not turn much but the bounce will be as good as yesterday and Shoaib Bashir and Glenn Phillips will enjoy it.

Brydon Carse is in for a chat. He starts by addressing the fact that the wickets here are more seamer-friendly than what they got last week. Further adds that the bounce from a length has helped him in all the dismissals so far and has kept all the seamers interested. Mentions that the medical team working behind the scenes have helped him in his recovery and he's feeling good at the moment.

The home side will depend on Tom Blundell, who is in his early days in his innings, and Glenn Phillips, who is yet to come, to narrow down the deficit, which currently stands at 194 runs. The English bowlers will be keen to wrap up the New Zealand innings quickly by making use of the morning conditions conducive to swing and seam. Usually, day three is known to be a moving day in a Test match, but looking at how fast this Test match has gone, Day 2 could well be that day. It certainly promises to be crucial in determining the balance of the match. Stay tuned for what is sure to be an exciting Day 2 at the Cello Basin Reserve!

For New Zealand, their top order crumbled under pressure from England’s bowlers. Kane Williamson showed resilience at the crease but didn’t last long enough to make a significant contribution. The biggest concern for the Kiwis was the quick fall of wickets - from 53-2, they slumped to 79/5, with the likes of Devon Conway, Daryl Mitchell, and Rachin Ravindra, failing to get going. England’s bowlers, led by Brydon Carse, were relentless, and the New Zealanders will need a sharp recovery if they are to avoid conceding a big lead.

England’s day was defined by Harry Brook’s brilliant knock of 123 runs off 115 balls, which was the standout performance of the innings. Brook’s knock played a pivotal role in rescuing England from a precarious 43-4. Ollie Pope’s 66 provided solid support in a 174-run partnership with Brook, and despite a flurry of wickets falling, England reached 280. However, the tail could not add much, and New Zealand's bowlers, Matt Henry, William O'Rourke and the local boy Nathan Smith with his 4-fer ensured England couldn’t get away with a massive total.

Hello and welcome to Day 2 of the second Test between New Zealand and England at the Cello Basin Reserve! After a thrilling opening day filled with dramatic twists and turns where 15 wickets fell, it’s safe to say that England would have walked off the field as the happier of the two teams. As we head into Day 2 of this Test, all eyes will be on how the pitch, which helped the pacers throughout the opening day, continues to evolve and which team can seize the upper hand.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 ...

With 194 runs adrift and only Glenn Phillips remaining as the recognized batter in the shed, New Zealand are firmly on the back foot. The wicket, offering lateral movement throughout the day, has made batting a challenge for everyone, and the hosts will need to dig deep. It promises to be yet another entertaining day of Test cricket. The first ball on Day 2 will be bowled at 10 pm GMT, but as always, you can join us earlier for the build-up. For now, you can switch tabs and follow the action from the Day-Night Test in Adelaide between Australia and India. Cheers!

In reply, New Zealand were dealt an early blow with the dismissal of Devon Conway. Just as a steady partnership was building between Kane Williamson and Tom Latham, the Kiwi skipper dragged one onto his stumps. From there, the hosts struggled, losing wickets at regular intervals. Williamson did have a bit of luck on 20 when he was bowled off a no-ball from Carse, but it was Carse who made amends. He got the breakthrough again, dismissing Williamson after he had managed to add only 17 more runs.

Harry Brook led the charge with his free-flowing batting, while Ollie Pope was the more compact of the two. After the break, Brook continued his attack, bringing up his century off 91 balls, while Pope also reached his fifty. The departure of Pope gave the hosts an opening, and they pounced on it to trigger a collapse. From 217/4, the tourists lost 6 for 63 to be bowled out for 280.

Earlier in the day, the game began under glorious sunshine, with the deck not as green as usual. As has been the tradition at the Cello Basin Reserve, New Zealand won the toss and opted to bowl first. The tourists were rocked early, with Matt Henry making full use of the movement off the deck to dismiss both English openers. It didn’t take long for the local boy Nathan Smith to make an impact, chipping in with a couple of wickets of his own. The first hour went the way of New Zealand, reducing England to 43/4. However, the next couple of hours saw England counterpunch.

Wow, what a day! 15 wickets fell, the joint-most on the opening day at the Cello Basin Reserve. Without a doubt, it was England's day out and out, and they will walk off the field the happier of the two sides. As for New Zealand, they will walk off with disappointment written large. They did well to restrict England to 280 after it seemed like they might post a much higher total, but it was their batting that let them down.

Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back for New Zealand's reply. The wind has picked up as the two umpires and players head out to the centre. It will be Tom Latham and Devon Conway to open the innings for New Zealand. Chris Woakes has the new ball in hand and he is raring to go. Off we go then...
... THE FOURTH INNINGS ...

For New Zealand, it's a mixed blessing - they have been spared further toil in the field, but now the true test begins with the bat. Their first-innings performance was anything but resilient, and chasing 583 runs, a target that has never been achieved in the history of Test cricket, will require an extraordinary, record-breaking effort. While time isn’t a constraint, the sheer scale of the task is monumental. The hosts will need to begin positively and focus on stitching partnerships in testing overcast conditions. Back in a bit for the fourth inning of the game.

Well, England have pulled the plug! They have declared with a commanding lead of 582 runs. After the overnight declaration didn't materialize, it seemed their priority was to give Joe Root a chance to reach his century, as he resumed the day on 73. Root wasted little time, racing to his 36th Test ton and the declaration came soon after his dismissal, with Ben Stokes remaining unbeaten on 49. Earlier in the innings, Jacob Bethell and Ben Duckett set the tone with intent-filled knocks, though both fell agonizingly short of their centuries. Root, however, ensured England's innings ended on a high. As for New Zealand, Nathan Smith and William O'Rourke bowled their hearts out, but fortune eluded them.

OUT! CAUGHT! Edged and taken! Bowled full and outside off, nips away off the wicket. Joe Root is drawn into the shot and goes for the drive away from his body. The outside edge is found and it goes low to the right of Tom Blundell who dives and sticks out his right glove. The ball does seem to slip out of his grasp and it is referred upstairs. The replays show that Blundell just about manages to hold onto the catch even after making hard contact with the ground. Root falls for 106 and with his departure, the declaration comes from England. They end with a lead of 582 runs.

Commentary.Commentary: We are all set for the action to start on Day 3. A windy and overcast morning greets the two umpires and players make their way out to the middle. William O'Rourke will kickstart proceedings with the ball for New Zealand. O'Rourke to Stokes first up. Here we go!

PITCH REPORT - Katey Martin and Shane Bond are near the deck. Katey informs that there is a strong breeze blowing across the ground and it can go up to 90 kph. Bond spots a few divots on the surface and feels that it's a sign of the pitch being on the drier side. Further says that the surface will still be good for batting. Feels that the wind will be a big challenge for the pacers and it is something they will have to account for while bowling.

Jacob Bethell is up for a quick chat. He says about his dismissal that it wasn't a very nice way to get out in that fashion. Mentions about the pitch that there is uneven bounce and it is a bit two-paced. Adds that it hasn't flattened out completely and hopefully, there is something for their bowlers when they come out to bowl. Adds that plans keep changing from inning to inning and every bowler has a different plan. Mentions that he loves batting with Ben Duckett and has had good partnerships in the limited-overs format. Concludes by saying that when they come out to bowl, they are hoping to take those ten wickets today itself.

There is still a lot of cricket to be played. Whenever the declaration comes, New Zealand will have to put up a fight, especially in the top order with the likes of Kane Williamson leading the charge and other batters to bat around him if they are to get anywhere close to the total. The pitch did show signs of easing out as Day 2 progressed but if the conditions stay overcast as the forecast suggests, it could create opportunities for the seamers. Stick around as the first ball on Day 3 is not far away.

New Zealand, on the other hand, struggled in their first innings. They began their innings with a decent start, but wickets fell regularly throughout. Kane Williamson was the only batter to offer any real challenge to England's bowlers. The Kiwis were bundled out for just 125 runs and from there on, it was just one-way traffic on Day 2. An overnight declaration could be on the cards, as England look to put New Zealand under some pressure by taking advantage of the early morning conditions and looking to wrap up New Zealand's innings on Day 3 itself.

England's dominance on Day 2 was highlighted by their remarkable batting performance, where they built on their 155-run lead and extended it to 533 by the end of the day. Barring Zak Crawley and Ollie Pope, all batters piled on the misery on New Zealand, though Ben Duckett and Jacob Bethell missed out on what could have been dominant and classy centuries. England's aggressive yet controlled approach was evident, with the team amassing runs at a healthy rate, with no maiden overs in all of England's second innings yet.

Hello and welcome to Day 3 of the second Test match between New Zealand and England at the Cello Basin Reserve in Wellington! Day 2 saw England firmly asserting their dominance with a spectacular display of both batting and bowling, leaving New Zealand with much to ponder as they head into Day 3.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

Not a single maiden over in 76 overs highlights that New Zealand have not been able to produce any genuine periods of pressure. With the second new ball only four overs old, the hosts will be eager to capitalize on the early morning conditions on Day 3. Meanwhile, England, sitting in a position of absolute dominance, will look to double down and extend their already massive lead. There is a forecast for scattered showers on Day 3, but let's hope the rain stays away. The first ball on Day 3 will be bowled at 10 pm GMT, but you can join us early for the build-up. The excitement on this action-packed weekend is far from over. Not far from Wellington, over in Adelaide, Day 2 of the Day-Night Test between Australia and India is underway. Later in the day, you can also follow Day 3's proceedings of the second Test between South Africa and Sri Lanka. You can switch tabs and keep track of those games. Cheers!

Gus Atkinson is down for a quick chat. He says that they started the day pretty well and the plan was to go hard right up top and it came off. Further adds that getting the hat-trick felt good but never actually thought of taking a hat-trick in a Test match.  Mentions that he doesn't want to speak too soon about his rhythm and feels that he is slowly getting back into the groove. In terms of game plans for bowling, he says that they will stick to the usual stuff and try and challenge the batters as much as they can and if that doesn't work they will look to do something else.

Joe Root and Harry Brook then took charge, adding to New Zealand's woes. The third session began on a more measured note, with Root and Brook adopting a steady approach rather than launching an all-out attack. Both batters maintained a healthy scoring rate as they reached well-deserved fifties. Brook eventually fell while attempting a big shot, and Ollie Pope followed soon after, dismissed cheaply. Ben Stokes, however, wasted no time, teeing off from ball one, raising the prospect of a late declaration. That, however, did not materialize as Root and Stokes batted through the remainder of the day with a commanding lead of 533 runs.

In response, England lost Zak Crawley cheaply, but Ben Duckett and Jacob Bethell led a spirited counterattack. Both batters adopted an aggressive yet calculated approach, finding boundaries with ease while rotating the strike effectively. However, as their respective hundreds approached, the tempo slowed noticeably, with both showing signs of nerves in the nineties. Neither could reach the milestone, but their efforts laid a solid foundation for England.

The day began with New Zealand trailing by 194 runs and desperately looking to narrow the deficit with five wickets in hand. However, Brydon Carse delivered a double blow in the fourth over of the morning, dismantling the hosts' hopes. Gus Atkinson then stole the spotlight with a stunning hat-trick, wrapping up the innings as New Zealand lost 5 for 39 to be bowled out for 125, conceding a hefty 155-run lead.

SESSION SUMMARY - 33 overs, 163 runs, and 2 wickets. For the second day in a row, England have stamped their authority and firmly established themselves in the driver’s seat. While Day 3 is traditionally considered the 'moving day' in Test cricket, this match has been progressing at a breakneck pace, and it seems the moving day has arrived a day early. With England extending their stranglehold, the game appears to have moved well beyond New Zealand’s grasp.

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks break! At the start of the session, the curiosity centred on how England would approach their innings. Well, we have our answer as Harry Brook and Joe Root have batted with intent yet sensibly. The pair has ticked along at a good clip and have extended the lead to 450 runs. For New Zealand, it’s been a tough grind in the field, with little happening to trouble the batters as England continue to pile on the misery.

FOUR! FIFTY FOR BROOK! Short of a length, outside off, from over the wicket, Harry Brook plays an upper cut deftly over the slip cordon and gets a boundary towards the deep third fence to reach his fifty. Another good innings by the centurion of the first innings.

... DAY 2, SESSION 3 ...

As Duckett and Bethell approached their respective centuries, the scoring rate dipped slightly, with Duckett looking notably tentative in the nervous nineties. Both batters ultimately missed out on their hundreds, something New Zealand will take some solace in, as they managed to deny the milestones. However, it was still another challenging session in the field for the hosts, with England firmly in control and stretching their lead to 370 runs. True to their proactive style, it wouldn’t be surprising if England put their foot on the gas after the break, looking to accelerate and possibly have New Zealand batting before the day’s end. Back in a bit for the third session.

SESSION SUMMARY - 28 overs, 133 runs and 2 wickets. Another session bossed by England in this Test! Ben Duckett and Jacob Bethell continued their impressive partnership after the Lunch break, scoring at a brisk pace. It wasn’t all about aggressive shot-making as the duo also displayed smart cricket by rotating the strike with well-judged singles and twos. New Zealand desperately needed someone to contain the scoring, but they couldn’t entirely stem the flow of runs.
Ends with a short ball, just outside off, Harry Brook clears his front leg and gets enough room to slap it wide of cover for three runs. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 2!

OUT! CAUGHT! Jacob Bethell's entertaining inning comes to an end and misses out on what could have been his maiden Test century. Bowled full and just outside off, nips just that slight bit away off the wicket. Jacob Bethell is drawn into the drive, goes for it and takes a faint outside edge. The keeper, Tom Blundell does the rest behind the wicket. New Zealand are ecstatic. Bethell falls 4 runs short of a hundred. The 187-run stand is broken. England are 196/2, leading by 351 runs.

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks break! England continue to pile on the runs, adding 79 runs in just 15 overs since the Lunch break, extending their lead to 316 runs. The partnership has not been solely about boundaries, as both batters have cleverly rotated the strike with well-placed singles and twos. For New Zealand, it is imperative that someone steps up to stem the flow of runs and maintain control from one end.

Commentary.Commentary: All in readiness for the second session of the day to commence. Tom Latham and his men take their respective positions on the field. Tim Southee is at the top of his mark and he is raring to go. Southee to Duckett first up. Two slips and a gully in place. Let's play...
... DAY 2, SESSION 2 ...

The highlight was Gus Atkinson's stunning hat-trick, which wrapped up the New Zealand innings. Atkinson also ended with 4 wickets, leaving New Zealand no chance to recover. With a 155-run lead, England's openers came out firing. Zak Crawley set the tone with two boundaries off the first two balls but fell quickly. However, Ben Duckett and Jacob Bethell steadied the ship with an unbeaten 73-run partnership, playing some confident strokes to keep England in control. What lies ahead? Can New Zealand fight back and limit England's lead, or will England extend their advantage to an insurmountable total by the end of the day? You can join us after the break at 12.40 am GMT to find out. Don’t go anywhere!

A fantastic session for England where they continued their dominance with the ball before extending their advantage with the bat! All smiles around in the English camp as they head to the Lunch break with a lead of 237 runs. New Zealand started the day at 86/5, hoping to narrow down the deficit, but things didn't go as planned. They were bowled out for just 125, unable to cope with England's relentless bowling attack. Brydon Carse continued his magic from the opening day, picking up another two wickets to finish with a brilliant 4-wicket haul.

Commentary.Commentary: Right then, it turned out to be a resounding, series-sealing victory for Ben Stokes and his men. A lot for Tom Latham and Co. to reflect on before the third Test. The caravan now moves north to Hamilton for the third and final Test of the series. It promises to be a memorable occasion for Tim Southee, who will play his farewell Test in his hometown. New Zealand will be eager to give their veteran pacer a fitting send-off with a victory. The third Test begins on Saturday, 14th December, at Seddon Park, with the first ball scheduled for 10 pm GMT. As always, you can join us early for the build-up to what promises to be an emotional and action-packed finale. Until then, take care and goodbye!

Ben Stokes, the captain of England says that it is amazing to stand here and win the series. Adds that he thinks that Harry Brook and Ollie Pope were amazing in this match, especially on day one where they batted with bravery and showed their skills. Says that it was an unbelievable inning from Brook and that set up the game for them. Tells that the instructions were to just play with freedom. Talks about Bethell that he played really well at number three. Adds that he wants to give opportunities to new guys and Bethell has the talent to stay here. Tells that there was always going to be pressure on New Zealand to chase down the target. Feels that their bowling was exceptional in these conditions where they bowled against the wind. Concludes that Chris Woakes has been exceptional in this match too and he has a lot of experience.

The captain of New Zealand, Tom Latham says that it is disappointing to lose in this fashion. Mentions that Harry Brook took the game away from them and he praises him for the way he played. States that the English team kept them under pressure throughout the game and didn't take the foot off the pedal. Says that the guys tried really hard and he is not doubting their efforts. Further adds that they came up with hopes of putting up a fight and they are obviously not happy with the performance. Concludes by saying that they will turn up at Hamilton and with it being the last Test for Tim Southee, they will look to make it a memorable occasion for him.

Harry Brook is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH for scoring 123 in the first innings and he followed it up with a fifty in the second innings. He says that he is happy to rescue the side after they were in early trouble at 43/4. Adds that the ball was swinging in the first innings and feels that the best form of defence is attack and he is happy to have done that. Mentions that it was an exceptional win and to win in three days, made it more special. Concludes that it is always amazing to win the series, and it is a record in itself for winning the series in NZ.
Time for the presentation ceremony...

Mitchell fell, but Blundell, who was dropped on 0 by Bethell, continued on his merry way as he marched to his 5th Test century. Nathan Smith batted with similar intent, and although their efforts did little to alter the result, both batters would have gained plenty of confidence from their knocks. England's bowlers, however, remained relentless. Ben Stokes brought himself into the attack and wrapped things up in style, claiming three wickets in as many overs to seal a dominant victory by 323 runs.

With a mammoth lead at the start of Day 3, many wondered if England would declare overnight, but that wasn’t the case. They continued their batting indulgence, and the declaration came soon after Joe Root departed immediately after his 36th Test century as the tourists ended with a lead of 582 runs. New Zealand were put out of their misery in the field as the declaration finally came, but their woes with the bat continued. Their top four were blown away in the morning session by the English pace trio of Woakes, Carse, and Atkinson. However, Daryl Mitchell and Tom Blundell stood firm and offered some much-needed resistance.

New Zealand’s response was lacklustre, with the English pacers dominating proceedings. Brydon Carse's incisive bowling brought him four wickets, but the moment of the innings belonged to Gus Atkinson, who delivered a stunning hat-trick to decimate the Kiwi tail. The hosts folded for just 125, conceding a hefty 155-run lead. After wrapping up the Kiwi innings within the first hour on Day 2, the visitors piled on the runs in their second innings. Ben Duckett and Jacob Bethell both fell agonizingly short of centuries, but their contributions, along with vital knocks from Harry Brook and Joe Root, helped the tourists extend their lead to 533 by the end of the day.

A three-day finish, and it felt as though the Test was in fast-forward mode throughout. So, let’s press the rewind button and take you back to where it all began - the opening day. It all began with New Zealand opting to bowl first, a decision that paid them early dividends as England were reduced to 43/4 in the opening session. However, Harry Brook and Ollie Pope staged a brilliant counterattack, stitching together a 174-run partnership. Brook notched up his second century of the series, but England's hopes of a massive total were dashed as they lost 6 wickets for just 63 runs to be bowled out for 280.

England complete a thumping win to seal the series! This victory marks their first Test series triumph in New Zealand since 2008. As for New Zealand, this result will sting. Coming into the series riding high after a 3-0 sweep in India, they have failed to turn up for the second Test in a row on home soil. Their batting woes have been glaring, with no partnerships reaching the three-figure mark so far in the series. The 96-run stand between Blundell and Smith in the second innings of this Test stands as their highest - a telling statistic of their struggles.

Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back for what could well be the final session of the Test. Ben Stokes leads his troops out to the centre. England are starting with spin in the form of Shoaib Bashir. Bashir to Blundell first up. Here we go!
.. DAY 3, SESSION 3 ...

However, as we've often seen, a break in play can bring a wicket, and it did just that as Mitchell was dismissed immediately after the drinks break. Glenn Phillips then took on Shoaib Bashir, but it was the off-spinner who eventually emerged victorious in their battle. Blundell, however, continued to play his shots with authority, and Nathan Smith joined him in and soon followed suit in putting the bad balls away. From a Kiwi perspective, it’s about salvaging positives and a century here for Blundell would do wonders for his confidence. Can England claim the remaining 4 wickets in the third session, or will New Zealand show defiance and take the Test to the 4th day? Stay tuned to find out!

SESSION SUMMARY - 29.5 overs, 140 runs and 2 wickets. An entertaining session overall, where England managed to take two crucial wickets to inch closer to wrapping up the game. However, New Zealand displayed positive intent with the bat, maintaining a run rate of 4.69. Daryl Mitchell and Tom Blundell batted with a calm composure through the early part of the second session, gradually growing in confidence as the innings progressed. With not much happening off the pitch, the pair negotiated the first part of the session without much trouble.

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks break! This has been a much-needed steady start to the second session for New Zealand. Daryl Mitchell and Tom Blundell have shown positive intent, gradually growing in confidence with each passing over. While the pitch hasn’t entirely eased out, the lateral movement has noticeably reduced compared to the challenging conditions of the first session. Despite their imposing total, England have adopted slightly defensive fields, allowing the batters to milk Shoaib Bashir for singles with ease. Gus Atkinson returns to the attack, replacing Chris Woakes.

Commentary.Commentary: As we had hoped, the rain has blown away and we are all set to get going in the second session. Harry Brook is yet to take the field today, sitting out as a precautionary measure due to a sore ankle. Rehan Ahmed continues as the substitute fielder. Gus Atkinson will resume things with the ball for England. Atkinson to Mitchell. Let's play...
... DAY 3, SESSION 2 ...

Woakes followed it up with the prized scalp of Kane Williamson. England's relentless attack continued as Brydon Carse took a sharp return catch to dismiss skipper Tom Latham, leaving New Zealand reeling and followed it by nicking Rachin Ravindra off just as the drizzle arrived. Daryl Mitchell has shown some positive intent and that is the way to go on this wicket where the ball is seaming around just enough to keep the batters on their toes. New Zealand face an uphill battle with four wickets already lost. Can England continue their charge and get the remaining six wickets in the next session itself, or will New Zealand’s middle order resist? Let’s hope the strong winds blowing today help drive the rain away for a prompt start to the second session. Stick around for all the action!

Daryl Mitchell pulls away as raindrops begin to interfere, seemingly getting into his eyes. The drizzle has picked up and the umpires have had enough. The players go off and with this, it will be LUNCH on Day 3. England dominated the session and they head into the break firmly on top of the Test match. They have taken four top-order wickets, and New Zealand are clearly struggling here. Resuming at 378/5 overnight, Joe Root reached his 36th Test century with some classy strokes before falling to William O’Rourke. England declared their innings at 427/6, setting New Zealand a daunting target of 583 runs. The chase began poorly for New Zealand as Chris Woakes went through the defences of Devon Conway in the third over.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! And now Williamson goes! Bowled on a length, from wide of the crease on the over-the-wicket angle, with a scrambled seam, nips away off the pitch. Kane Williamson is already standing on the off stump and gets himself into a position that he has to play at it. The ball takes a faint outside edge and the keeper Ollie Pope completes a regulation catch in the end. New Zealand are 25/2.
Commentary.Howout: c Ollie Pope b Chris Woakes
Commentary.Default_Commentary: 6.6: Chris Woakes to Kane Williamson, OUT! c Ollie Pope b Chris Woakes.

OUT! BOWLED! The woes continue for New Zealand. Coming in from around the wicket, Woakes bowls it full and just outside off stump, nips in. Devon Conway is trapped inside his crease and he is unsure which way the ball will go. He tries to play at it by getting his hands out in front. The ball comes back in, goes past the inside and just clips the off bail on its way.
